# Enforce CRLF on disk for every text file, regardless of any
# contributor's core.autocrlf / core.eol settings.
#
# How this works: `text=auto` tells git to detect whether a file is
# text or binary at add-time. For text files, the blob is stored with
# LF in the repo (git's normalization), and converted to CRLF on
# checkout (`eol=crlf`). Binary files are left untouched.
#
# .gitattributes overrides per-user git config, so a Linux contributor
# whose `core.autocrlf` is `input` and a Windows contributor whose
# `core.autocrlf` is `true` will both end up with CRLF in their
# working tree.

* text=auto eol=crlf

# Belt-and-suspenders: explicitly mark known binary extensions so the
# auto-detect can't get it wrong on a malformed/edge-case file.
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
*.jpeg  binary
*.gif   binary
*.ico   binary
*.zip   binary
